    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cheney's Rosy Future</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alex Taylor letter comments on August 12 article on Republican vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney's $20 million retirement package from Halliburton Co</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Cheney Is Said to Be Receiving $20 Million Retirement Package'' (front page, Aug. 12):</p>
        <p>The fact that under Dick Cheney's watch the Halliburton Company ''laid off thousands of employees and reduced retirees' medical benefits'' raises questions as to the true nature of Republican discourse. Those questions become even more pressing when one considers the $20 million retirement package for Mr. Cheney approved by Halliburton's board of directors.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Cheney Is Said to Be Receiving $20 Million Retirement Package'' (front page, Aug. 12):</p>
        <p>The fact that under Dick Cheney's watch the Halliburton Company ''laid off thousands of employees and reduced retirees' medical benefits'' raises questions as to the true nature of Republican discourse. Those questions become even more pressing when one considers the $20 million retirement package for Mr. Cheney approved by Halliburton's board of directors.</p>
        <p>Is laying off thousands of employees so that they can subsidize the obscene salaries of America's chief executives the sort of ''compassionate conservatism'' that the Bush-Cheney ticket has in mind for this country?</p>
        <p>ALEX TAYLOR  Washington, Aug. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
